activity.p:
To find the least common multiple of 12 and 32, we will start off by factoring out the greatest common
factor from each number:

	\begin{array}{lcl}
		12 \amp = \amp 4 \cdot 3 \\
		32 \amp = \amp 4 \cdot 8
	\end{array}

Notice that the common factor is already shared between the two numbers, so we can leave that part alone.
The remaining parts are what we might call "unshared" factors. Each part is missing the other's unshared
factor, and so those are the things we need to multiply by to find the least common multiple.

	\begin{array}{rclcl}
		12 \cdot 8 \amp = \amp (4 \cdot 3) \cdot 8 \amp = \amp 96 \\
		32 \cdot 3 \amp = \amp (4 \cdot 8) \cdot 3 \amp = \amp 96
	\end{array}

This same approach can be used for finding common multiples of variable expressions. We will use it to find
the least common multiple of 9x^2y and 15x y^4.

	\left.
		\begin{array}{lcl}
			9x^2 y \amp = \amp 3xy \cdot 3x \\
			15xy^4 \amp = \amp 3xy \cdot 5y^3
		\end{array}
	\right\} \longrightarrow
	\left\{
		\begin{array}{lcl}
			9x^2 y \cdot 5y^3 \amp = \amp 45x^2y^4 \\
			15xy^4 \cdot 3x \amp = \amp 45x^2y^4
		\end{array}
	\right.

p.me:
\left. \begin{array}{ll}
	4a^2b^3 \amp = 4a^2 b \cdot b^2 \\
	12a^3 b \amp = 4a^2 b \cdot 3a
\end{array} \right\}
\longrightarrow
\left\{ \begin{array}{lll}
	4a^2b^3 \cdot 3a \amp = 12a^3 b^3 \\
	12a^3 b \cdot b^2 \amp = 12a^3 b^3
\end{array} \right.

activity.p:
Here is the calculation of \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3}: 

	\begin{aligned}
		\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3} \amp = \frac{1 \cdot 3}{2 \cdot 3} + \frac{1 \cdot 2}{3 \cdot 2}
			\amp \eqnspacer \amp \text{Common denominator} \\
		\amp = \frac{3}{6} + \frac{2}{6} \\
		\amp = \frac{5}{6} 
	\end{aligned}

The same logic can be applied to adding or subtracting fractions with variables in them. Sometimes you will
be able to combine like terms, and sometimes you won't. You simply need to pay attention to the information
that's in front of you. 

	\begin{aligned}
		\frac{2x}{y} + \frac{3y}{x^2} \amp = \frac{2x \cdot x^2}{y \cdot x^2} + \frac{3y \cdot y}{x^2 \cdot y}
			\amp \eqnspacer \amp \text{Common denominator} \\
		\amp = \frac{2x^3}{x^2y} + \frac{3y^2}{x^2y} \\
		\amp = \frac{2x^3 + 3y^2}{x^2y} 
	\end{aligned}
